  • Annotation Types Summary
    Annotation Type Description
    AllowsInterrupt
    Annotation indicating that this method or constructor increases the statement time, or allows the execution to be interrupted.
    BeforeMark
    Opposite of @E1Immutable @E2Immutable as a dynamic type annotation on fields and methods.
    Constant
    A field has been assigned, or a method returns, a constant value.
    Container
    Implies that no method of this type modifies its parameters.
    Dependent
    Opposite of @Independent.
    Dependent1
    "content dependent"
    Dependent2
    "content dependent"
    E1Container
    Annotation marking that the type is effectively or eventually level 1 immutable (all fields are (eventually) @Final), and the type is a container.
    E1Immutable
    Annotation marking that the type is effectively or eventually level 1 immutable (all fields are (eventually) @Final).
    E2Container  
    E2Immutable  
    ExtensionClass
    Annotation indicating that a type is an extension class.
    Final
    Annotation indicating that a field is effectively or eventually final.
    Finalizer
    Annotation indicating that the method returns 'this'.
    Fluent
    Annotation indicating that the method returns 'this'.
    Identity
    Annotation indicating that the method returns its first parameter.
    IgnoreModifications
    Annotation used to indicate that modifications on a field can be ignored.
    Independent
    Annotation indicating that the method or constructor is not linked to its support data parameters.
    Linked
    Annotation for debugging purposes: explains if and where a field links to.
    Linked1
    Annotation for debugging purposes: explains if and where a field content links to.
    Mark
    Annotation to mark a modifying method.
    Modified
    Opposite of @NotModified
    Modified1
    Used for parameters of abstract types
    MutableModifiesArguments
    Present when a type is neither @Container nor @E1Immutable.
    NotModified
    Indicates that no modifications took place in the method; that the parameter's content was not modified, that no method modifies the content of the field.
    NotModified1
    Used for functional types, as a dynamic type annotation, to indicate that the single abstract method does not modify either parameter or variables in the closure.
    NotNull
    On a method, indicates that it never returns null.
    NotNull1
    Content not null, one level up from not null.
    NotNull2
    Marks that the content of content is not null
    Nullable
    Opposite of NotNull
    Only
    As part of the eventual computations, @Only methods can either be executed before or after a mark.
    PropagateModification
    Indicates that an abstract method has been called on this parameter, and modification needs propagating at the place of calling
    Singleton  
    TestMark
    Annotation to mark a non-modifying method, returning a boolean on whether the mark has been achieved or not
    UtilityClass
    Annotation on a type to indicate that the type is a properly defined utility class.
    Variable
    Opposite of @Final
